SIMPLE: fleet
RECORDS: 6

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: fleet
<hw>fleet</hw> <pr>(fl⟦emac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>fleeted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>fleeting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>fleten</ets>,
<ets>fleoten</ets>, to swim, AS. <ets>fle⟦oacute⟧tan</ets> to swim,
float; akin to D. <ets>vlieten</ets> to flow, OS. <ets>fliotan</ets>,
OHG. <ets>fliozzan</ets>, G. <ets>fliessen</ets>, Icel.
<ets>flj⟦omac⟧ta</ets> to float, flow, Sw. <ets>flyta</ets>, D.
<ets>flyde</ets>, L. <ets>pluere</ets> to rain, Gr. <grk>plei^n</grk> to
sail, swim, float, Skr. <ets>plu</ets> to swim, sail. ⟦root⟧84. Cf.
<er>Fleet</er>, <pos>n. & a.</pos>, <er>Float</er>, <er>Pluvial</er>,
<er>Flow</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To sail; to float.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And in frail wood on Adrian Gulf doth <qex>fleet</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fly swiftly; to pass over quickly; to hasten; to
flit as a light substance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the unaccomplished works of Nature's hand, . . . ⟦br⟧
Dissolved on earth, <qex>fleet</qex> hither.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To slip on the whelps or the
barrel of a capstan or windlass; -- said of a cable or hawser.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To move or change in position; --
said of persons; <as>as, the crew <ex>fleeted</ex> aft</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fleet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fleet
<hw>Fleet</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pass over rapidly;
to skin the surface of; <as>as, a ship that <ex>fleets</ex> the
gulf</as>.</def> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To hasten over; to cause to pass away lightly, or in
mirth and joy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Many young gentlemen flock to him, and <qex>fleet</qex> the time
carelessly.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To draw apart the
blocks of; -- said of a tackle.</def> <rj><au>Totten.</au></rj></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>To cause to slip down the barrel of a capstan or
windlass, as a rope or chain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To move or change in position;
used only in special phrases; <as>as, of <ex>fleet aft</ex> the
crew</as>.</def></p>

<p><q>We got the long ⟦ldquo⟧stick⟦rdquo⟧ . . . down and
⟦ldquo⟧<qex>fleeted</qex>⟦rdquo⟧ aft, where it was secured.</q>
<rj><qau>F. T. Bullen.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fleet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fleet
<hw>Fleet</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Fleeter</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Fleetest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[Cf. Icel. <ets>flj⟦omac⟧tr</ets>
quick. See <er>Fleet</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Swift in motion; moving with velocity; light and quick in going
from place to place; nimble.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In mail their horses clad, yet <qex>fleet</qex> and strong.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Light; superficially thin; not penetrating deep, as
soil.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Mortimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fleet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Fleet
<hw>Fleet</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>flete</ets>,
<ets>fleote</ets>, AS. <ets>fle⟦oacute⟧t</ets> ship, fr.
<ets>fle⟦oacute⟧tan</ets> to float, swim. See <er>Fleet</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos> and cf. <er>Float</er>.]</ety> <def>A number of vessels in
company, especially war vessels; also, the collective naval force of a
country, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fleet captain</b></col>, <cd>the senior aid of the
admiral of a fleet, when a captain.</cd> <rj><au>Ham. Nav.
Encyc.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fleet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Fleet
<hw>Fleet</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>fle⟦oacute⟧t</ets> a place
where vessels float, bay, river; akin to D. <ets>vliet</ets> rill,
brook, G. <ets>fliess</ets>. See <er>Fleet</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A flood; a creek or inlet; a bay or estuary; a river;
-- obsolete, except as a place name, -- as <xex>Fleet</xex> Street in
London.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Together wove we nets to entrap the fish⟦br⟧
In floods and sedgy <qex>fleets</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Matthewes.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A former prison in London, which originally stood
near a stream, the <xex>Fleet</xex> (now filled up).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fleet parson</b></col>, <cd>a clergyman of low character,
in, or in the vicinity of, the Fleet prison, who was ready to unite
persons in marriage (called <xex>Fleet marriage</xex>) at any hour,
without public notice, witnesses, or consent of parents.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fleet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Fleet
<hw>Fleet</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>fl⟦emac⟧t</ets> cream, fr. <ets>fle⟦oacute⟧tan</ets> to float. See
<er>Fleet</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <def>To take the cream from; to
skim.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fleeten</ent>⟦br⟧
